Team Diffy’s 50’s Update: Round 1 - Traxs Winter Series 

Bronson finished 3rd in his heat and was running great in the main but one of his friends crashed so he stopped to make sure he was ok before continuing on to a 6th place finish. 

Yes it would have cool to see him podium but I find it way more awesome that he was more concerned about a friend than a wooden plaque with a number on it, that’s better than a win in my book.  I feel honored to have a kid like Bronson riding one of my bikes. 
.

Update: Didn’t realize people would want to help this kid out and I guess we’re going to try and buy him a bike, link in my bio for PayPal, CashApp, & Venmo.  All donations go towards buying him a newer bike. 

Pretty sure this kid had the most fun out of anyone at MXR Arenacross, no idea who he is but he was talking to me, and if I remember correctly he was telling me how it was his first race and how excited he was. 

I definitely remember him telling me about his bike, which some might not think it’s much, but I think it’s pretty damn cool and so did he. 

Really hoping to see him at some more races with that same attitude, kids and even adults with his attitude make being at the track so much more enjoyable. 
.

Been doing some exploring this off season 🤙🏻

1 & 2: St Mary’s Mercy Hospital - Michael Jackson as well as @midwestfleshurbex and @thesteelcitystorm were born here.  Professional baseball player Lymon Bostock passed away here in 1978 after being shot.

3: Part of St. Mary’s Mercy Operating Room. 

4: City Methodist Church, probably one of the most explored places in the Midwest, maybe even America, she’s getting rough though.

5:  Seaman’s Hall in City Methodist.

6: Big Jim Colosimo, former Chicago Mob Boss, assassinated in 1920

7: The neglected Jewish section of Oak Wood Cemetery.

8: Confederate Mount, the largest mass burial in the Western Hemisphere.  More than 4,000 Confederate soldiers from Camp Douglas are buried here after being relocated. 

9: Cale Cramer, lost his life by saving a train in York, IN in 1887.  Those he saved raised funds to build this monument for him.

10: Last but not least, the original Aunt Jemima, Nancy Green.

Wish I would have got to see this place before it was trashed but I’m just happy I finally got to see it in person, I’ve been eyeing it for quite a few years now. 

Without seeing the before pictures you could just tell how much detail was put into building this school, the kind of detail you’ll never see in a schools again, so it’s always sad to see one like this wasting away. 
.
.
.

A few stops from Diffy’s Tour de Detroit ✌🏻

1-2: Michigan Theater - 8 Mile - Scene where they have a rap battle in the parking garage and Free World shows up, then a fight ensues.

3-4: New Detroit Stamping - 8 Mile - The place where B. Rabbit lands a good job, has a rap battle in the parking lot, and does the dirty with his girl. 

5-6: Garden Court Condos: Martin TV Show - The apartment building shown in the outside shots of Martin’s apartment although it was actually filmed on a set. 

7-10: Motown Records AKA Hitsville USA - Home of Berry Gordy’s record label from 1959 to 1968, shown outside in photos is Diana Ross & The Supremes, The Four Tops, & Smokey Robinson. 
.
.
.

So thankful to be able to use the reach you all have helped me create and do something good with it.

A little over 2 weeks ago Carter lost the person he called dad, Cody, in a tragic accident. 

Cody’s friends, who also happen to be friends of mine and supporters of DiffySmooth since day one, reached out to me to see if I could get Cody’s old XR50 going to give to Carter for his birthday like Cody had wanted to before he passed.  Knowing I could do it with the way you all support me on projects like this, I took on the task.  10 days later, lots of new parts, and some late nights, we made it happen. 

Once again, thank all of you who helped make this happen and any of you who have ever helped me, I try to help others when I can as a way to say thank you to those I could never repay for all the things they’ve done for me.  I also do it because I genuinely enjoy helping others and making a difference in people’s lives when I can. 

And just for the record I don’t post stuff like this in hopes of recognition, I post it in hopes that someone might see it and be motivated to help someone when they can.

Emerson High School after the fire last night that destroyed a majority of the roof and the East attic. 

Ralph Waldo Emerson High opened in 1908 and was Indiana’s first school with a pool and the first in the nation to introduce vocational classes into the curriculum. 

Closed as a high school in 1981 it continued to be used as a performing arts school until 2007, 1 year short of its 100 year anniversary.  Since then its sat unused, neglected, and slowly being torn apart by scrappers, and now multiple fires. 

I hate to say it but I have a feeling after this most recent fire, Emerson will soon meet the same fate of its sister schools Lew Wallace and Froebel.

Diffrod Does History Vol. 7: Hangar No. 3 at Chanute Air Force Base (Base Built 1917 & Hangar Built 1938)

Chanute Field was established on 21 May 1917, being one of thirty-two Air Service training camps established after the United States entry into World War I. 

Chanute Field was named in honor of Octave Chanute, a pioneer aeronautical engineer and experimenter, a friend and adviser to the Wright Brothers.

The airfield was completed on 22 July 1917 at a cost of about $1 million, and was officially accepted by the Air Service on 31 July.

Construction started on Hangar No. 3 in 1938 and appears the be mostly completed by 1939.  It is one of four hangars that dominate the landscape within the Chanute AFB Historic District. All four hangars were built in response to the massive mobilization required by World War II and served not only as hangars but as school laboratories from the time they were completed.

On 22 March 1941, the first all-black fighter squadron was activated at Chanute Field. Formed without pilots with the purpose of training the officer corps and ground support personnel, the 99th Pursuit Squadron was the first unit of what popularly became known as the Tuskegee Airmen. 

The base officially closed in 1993. 

Buildings have been torn down such White Hall, some remain empty, and a number have been repurposed such as Hangar No. 3 by @b52hangarmx ✈️

This is just a quick history, if you dig this I suggest you do a quick online search and you’ll find so much info on Chanute AFB.

So pumped on getting all 3 PW’s out on the ice today, plus one more, for the first ever running of the Wobbler class at Moto On Ice! 🏁

I honestly wasn’t sure how it was going to go because I couldn’t find any videos of anyone else doing it but I figured it was worth a shot and thankfully everyone loved it from the riders to the fans! 

Hoping we can get some more weekends in on the ice before the weather changes because it seemed like more people wanted to get in on the class once they saw it out there.

I know I say it all the time but I’ll say it again, a huge thank you to anyone who’s ever helped with Diffy’s 50’s, it means a lot to me to be able to give back and do this, I couldn’t do it without you!

Also a big thank you to all the parents and kids who came out and had fun, the smiles and laughs are what motivate me to keep doing my best with this!
